        <h1>A local comedy organizer is hoping these punchlines get people to the polls</h1>
        <div class="article-meta">October 30, 2024 • Community Reporting</div>
        
        <div class="video-container">
            <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/iKCEYuPBlrw" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
        </div>
        
        <p>On Thursday, Oct. 17, a collection of Boston-area comedians and comedy fans gathered at the Rockwell in Davis Square for "Jokes for Justice," a comedy show with an unusual purpose: to make sure attendees register and make a plan to vote in the 2024 election. Shelby Le Cuyer has been organizing this show for the past year, and as of this fourth show says they have "more than 150 voters confirmed with plans so far."</p>
        
        <p>Politics is the punchline at Jokes for Justice, which focuses on the inherent issues within the American political system while still recognizing the power of underrepresented communities exercising their voices through their votes.</p>
        
